      "Additional global privacy laws: Privacy Act of 1974 (US federal — governs federal agency data collection; grants individuals rights to access and correct records); CLOUD Act 2018 (US — allows law enforcement to compel US companies to produce data regardless of where stored globally; conflicts with GDPR data localisation); PIPL (China Personal Information Protection Law — strict data localisation, consent requirements, similar structure to GDPR); POPIA (South Africa Protection of Personal Information Act — 8 processing conditions); EU-US Data Privacy Framework 2023 (replaced Privacy Shield, which itself replaced Safe Harbor — mechanisms for lawful EU-US data transfers)",
      "FedRAMP (Federal Risk and Authorisation Management Program): US government programme standardising cloud security assessments so that a single authorisation can be reused across federal agencies; cloud providers must obtain ATO (Authority to Operate) assessed by an accredited 3PAO (Third-Party Assessment Organisation); three impact levels based on FIPS 199: Low (publicly available or non-sensitive data), Moderate (CUI — Controlled Unclassified Information; most federal data), High (law enforcement, emergency services, critical infrastructure); FedRAMP uses continuous monitoring with monthly/annual reporting obligations",
      "Security frameworks: SABSA (Sherwood Applied Business Security Architecture) = business-risk-driven enterprise security architecture with 6 layers — Contextual (business), Conceptual (architect), Logical (designer), Physical (builder), Component (tradesman), Operational (facilities) — each layer defines attributes, assets, processes, people, locations, and time; CIS Critical Security Controls = 18 prioritised, actionable controls (formerly Top 20) focused on highest-impact defences against real attacks; NIST SP 800-53 = comprehensive security and privacy control catalogue used by US federal agencies; NIST SP 800-30 = risk assessment methodology with structured threat source and vulnerability tables",
      "ISO/IEC 27000 series: 27000 (overview and vocabulary — definitions used across the series), 27001 (ISMS requirements — the only certifiable/auditable standard in the series; defines Annex A controls), 27002 (code of practice — implementation guidance for Annex A controls; not certifiable), 27017 (cloud-specific security controls extending 27002), 27018 (PII protection in public cloud — aligns with GDPR); NIST CSF 2.0 (2024): added 'Govern' as a 6th function (establish cybersecurity strategy, policy, roles, accountability, and risk appetite) to the original 5 functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover",
      "Supply chain security mechanisms: Silicon Root of Trust (RoT) = hardware anchor where cryptographic keys and integrity measurements are immutably stored in a dedicated chip (TPM or secure enclave) — provides the foundation for secure boot, firmware attestation, and platform trust; PUF (Physically Unclonable Function) = hardware fingerprint derived from unique manufacturing variations in silicon — physically unclonable, used for device authentication and secret key generation without storing keys; SBOM (Software Bill of Materials) = machine-readable inventory of all software components, versions, and dependencies — required by US Executive Order 14028 to identify supply chain vulnerabilities and licence obligations",
      "Employment lifecycle and legal agreements: Onboarding = NDA (Non-Disclosure Agreement — protects trade secrets and confidential information; survives employment), Non-compete agreement (limits competitive employment post-termination), AUP (Acceptable Use Policy — defines permitted use of organisational assets), background checks and reference verification before access is granted; Transfer = re-evaluate access rights to prevent privilege accumulation, update clearance; Offboarding = immediate account and access revocation, device return, exit interview, NDA reminder, and escort from premises; Mandatory vacations = forces duty coverage, exposing fraud; Job rotation = cross-trains and detects irregularities",
      "Security awareness programme design: Three tiers: Awareness (all employees — recognise and report threats; non-technical), Training (role-specific skills — hands-on for IT/security staff), Education (conceptual understanding for architects and managers); Security champions = designated employees who act as security advocates within their team — amplify security culture without central team having to cover all groups; Gamification = points, leaderboards, badges, and challenges to increase engagement and retention; Phishing simulation metrics: click rate (susceptibility), credential submission rate (severity), report rate (detection capability) — used to measure and target awareness training investment",
      "Intellectual property extensions: Patent types: Utility patent (new, useful processes, machines, or compositions of matter — 20-year protection), Design patent (ornamental appearance of a functional item — 15 years), Software patent (algorithms, methods, and processes implemented in software — jurisdiction-dependent); Economic Espionage Act (EEA) 1996 = US federal law criminalising theft of trade secrets by foreign governments or for commercial advantage — penalties include up to 15 years imprisonment; TRIPS (Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights) = WTO international IP enforcement standard that member states must implement",
      "Threat intelligence sharing standards: STIX (Structured Threat Information eXpression) = JSON-based language for describing threat intelligence objects including indicators, TTPs, threat actors, campaigns, and malware; TAXII (Trusted Automated eXchange of Indicator Information) = HTTPS-based transport protocol for sharing STIX content between organisations via push or pull subscriptions; together STIX and TAXII enable automated machine-readable threat intelligence exchange — compare with ISACs which are sector-specific human-curated sharing communities",
      "Additional risk assessment methodologies: OCTAVE (Operationally Critical Threat, Asset and Vulnerability Evaluation) = organisation-led, asset-driven approach conducted by internal business unit teams — focuses on enterprise-wide risk, not just IT systems; TARA (Threat Agent Risk Assessment) = risk assessment framework that identifies and scores threats based on threat agent likelihood and impact to produce a prioritised risk list; Hybrid risk analysis = combines quantitative formulas for high-value assets with qualitative judgement for context and intangibles — most practical approach for real organisations; ISO/IEC 31000 = international risk management standard providing universal principles, framework, and process guidance applicable to any organisation",
