      "Password security best practices: minimum length > complexity (exam tip); enforce uniqueness (prevent password reuse via history list); implement account lockout after failed attempts; use salted hashes (bcrypt, scrypt, Argon2) for storage; password spraying = trying one common password across many accounts; credential stuffing = using breached credential lists",
      "TEMPEST and emanation security: TEMPEST = US government standard controlling electromagnetic emanation from electronic equipment to prevent eavesdropping; Van Eck phreaking = capturing CRT/LCD emissions to reconstruct screen content; white noise generators and Faraday cages (conductive mesh) mitigate emanation attacks; SCIF (Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility) provides physical + emanation protection",
      "Account lifecycle: Provisioning (create account with minimum necessary rights) → Review (periodic entitlement review for least privilege) → Modification (update rights on role change) → Suspension (temporary disable, preserve audit trail) → Termination (immediate disable on separation — disable before delete to preserve logs); offboarding checklist: disable accounts, revoke tokens, retrieve devices",
      "Kerberos authentication: KDC (Key Distribution Center) contains AS (Authentication Server) and TGS (Ticket Granting Server); flow: (1) User requests TGT from AS, (2) AS issues TGT, (3) User presents TGT to TGS for service ticket, (4) Service ticket used to access resource; tickets are time-limited; Kerberoasting = extracting service tickets and cracking offline",
      "RADIUS vs TACACS+: RADIUS = UDP, encrypts only password, combines authentication and authorisation; TACACS+ (Cisco) = TCP, encrypts entire payload, separates authentication/authorisation/accounting (AAA) — TACACS+ more secure and granular but proprietary; both used for network device access control",
      "LDAP and Active Directory: LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) = protocol for querying and modifying X.500-based directory services; ports: 389 (cleartext), 636 (LDAPS/TLS); Active Directory = Microsoft's directory service implementing LDAP + Kerberos; AD structure: Forest (security/trust boundary) → Domain → Organisational Unit (OU) → Objects (users, computers, groups, GPOs); Group Policy Objects (GPOs) centrally enforce security settings — password policies, software restriction, audit configuration, firewall rules",
      "Federated identity management: allows authentication across organisational boundaries without sharing credentials; Identity Provider (IdP) = authenticates user and issues assertions/tokens; Service Provider (SP) = trusts IdP assertions and grants access without re-authenticating; SAML (XML-based federation standard) used for enterprise federation; Circle of Trust = group of IdPs and SPs with established trust; enables cross-domain SSO and B2B collaboration without exposing internal directories",
      "FIDO2 / WebAuthn passwordless authentication: FIDO2 = combination of WebAuthn (W3C browser API) + CTAP2 (Client to Authenticator Protocol); authenticators: hardware security keys (YubiKey, Titan Key) and platform biometrics (Windows Hello, Touch ID, Face ID); each registration creates a device-specific public-private key pair — private key never leaves the device or authenticator; phishing-resistant because the cryptographic proof is origin-bound (domain-specific) — a fake domain receives nothing useful",
      "Account types and security risks: Regular user (standard privileges); Service accounts (used by applications — disable interactive logon, use Group Managed Service Accounts (gMSA) for auto-rotating credentials); Shared/generic accounts (avoid — no individual accountability, cannot audit individual actions); Privileged/admin accounts (require PAM, JIT, MFA, and dedicated Privileged Access Workstation); Guest accounts (disable when not needed); Orphaned accounts (former employees with active credentials — highest insider threat risk, audit and disable immediately on offboarding)",
      "Identity Governance and Administration (IGA): automated lifecycle management through Joiner/Mover/Leaver (JML) workflow; Role mining = analysing actual access patterns to define correct RBAC roles; Access certification (attestation) = periodic manager review confirming each user's access remains appropriate; SoD (Segregation of Duties) conflict detection — IGA tools flag users with incompatible role combinations (e.g. raise-PO + approve-PO); regular recertification campaigns prevent entitlement creep",
      "TOTP vs HOTP (OTP standards): TOTP (RFC 6238) = time-based OTP valid for a 30-second window using HMAC(shared_secret, current_time) — most common in authenticator apps; HOTP (RFC 4226) = counter-based OTP, increments on each use, remains valid until used (vulnerable to desynchronisation); TOTP preferred because the time-bounded window limits replay risk; both are 'something you have' factors; TOTP requires clock synchronisation within ±30 sec tolerance",
