      "Zero Trust identity and CAE: Zero Trust identity principles: verify explicitly (authenticate every request using all signals), use least privilege (JIT access), assume breach (segment access, encrypt everything, log all activity); CAE (Continuous Access Evaluation) = tokens validated in near-real-time — access is revoked immediately when conditions change (account disabled, password changed, risky sign-in detected, IP change) rather than waiting for token natural expiry; implemented in Azure AD Conditional Access",
      "Diameter protocol (AAA for 4G/5G): successor to RADIUS; addresses RADIUS weaknesses including UDP transport, limited failover, and restricted attribute support; Diameter uses TCP or SCTP with built-in failover and roaming support; the primary AAA protocol for 4G LTE and 5G mobile networks (replaces RADIUS in mobile core); not backwards-compatible with RADIUS; extensible via application-specific Attribute-Value Pairs (AVPs); also referenced in Domain 4 as a 5G attack surface",
      "Pass-the-hash vs pass-the-ticket vs Golden Ticket: Pass-the-hash (PtH) = captures an NTLM password hash and uses it directly for authentication without knowing the cleartext password — exploits NTLM's lack of salted challenges; Pass-the-ticket (PtT) = steals a valid Kerberos TGT or service ticket and replays it for lateral movement; Golden Ticket = attacker who has obtained the KRBTGT account hash (via DCSync or DC compromise) forges a TGT granting persistent domain admin access; mitigated by Protected Users security group, Credential Guard, regular KRBTGT password rotation (twice in succession after compromise)",
      "Shoulder surfing and emanation attacks: Shoulder surfing = a physical observation attack where an attacker watches a victim's screen or keyboard in a public space or office to capture PINs, passwords, or other credentials — no technical tools required; mitigated by privacy screens, seating arrangements, and security awareness; related to TEMPEST (electronic emanation capture) but requires only direct line of sight rather than electronic equipment",
      "Mandatory Access Control (MAC) environment types: Hierarchical = security labels in a strict ordered sequence from low to high (Unclassified → Confidential → Secret → Top Secret); Compartmented = access to specific named compartments or domains regardless of hierarchical level (e.g. SCI codewords — a TS-cleared person may lack access to a specific codeword compartment); Hybrid = combines hierarchical labels with compartmented restrictions — most flexible and granular; used in US DoD and intelligence community systems",
      "Roles vs Groups: Roles = function-centric — a set of permissions corresponding to a job function (e.g. Helpdesk Analyst L1); users are assigned to a role and receive its permissions; RBAC assigns permissions to roles, not individuals; Groups = user-centric — a collection of users; admins assign permissions to the group rather than to each user individually; Windows AD uses groups as the primary mechanism; Roles focus on what the job needs, Groups focus on who is in the collection; both reduce admin overhead compared to per-user permission assignment",
      "Centralised vs decentralised access control: Centralised = single entity or system performs all authorisation verification — easier to manage, can scale from small to large, but creates a potential single point of failure; Decentralised (distributed) = multiple entities throughout a system perform authorisation — requires more admin staff spread across locations, inconsistency risk as changes must be replicated everywhere; identity is now the 'new perimeter' with ubiquitous mobile and cloud access",
      "Privilege escalation — horizontal, vertical, and lateral movement: Horizontal privilege escalation = attacker gains similar access level as the compromised account but from other user accounts (same privilege tier, different accounts); Vertical privilege escalation = attacker gains significantly higher privileges than the compromised account (e.g. standard user → local admin → domain admin); Lateral movement = combining horizontal escalation across multiple systems to expand access throughout the network; minimise service account privileges and audit sudo usage to reduce attack surface",
      "Session management: session created after successful identification, authentication, and authorisation; session management prevents unauthorised access by closing unattended sessions; termination strategies: schedule limitations (restrict hours of availability), login limitations (prevent simultaneous logins with same ID), time-outs (expire after inactivity period), screensavers (require re-authentication after idle); improper session management enables session hijacking — attacker takes over an authenticated session; OWASP publishes session management cheat sheets for developers",
      "Content-dependent vs context-dependent access control: Content-dependent = access decision is based on the actual content being accessed beyond basic auth — e.g. all employees can view the HR database for their own record but are denied access to a different employee's record; Context-dependent = applies additional situational context before granting access — e.g. time-of-day restrictions (access only during business hours), geolocation, device type; both add criteria beyond authentication and authorisation to make finer-grained access decisions",
      "Credential management and password vaults: credential management systems store usernames and passwords securely so users can log on automatically without re-entering credentials; password vault (password manager) = encrypted database of credentials protected by a master password or key; W3C published Credential Management Level 1 API (2019) adopted by many browsers; advantage: enables strong unique passwords per system without memorisation; risk: master password compromise exposes all stored credentials; enterprise vaults integrate with PAM platforms for privileged credential management",
      "Excessive privilege and privilege creep: excessive privilege = user account holds more permissions than their job tasks require — violates least privilege principle; creeping privileges (privilege creep) = user account accumulates additional privileges over time as job roles and tasks change without revoking old access; both are detected and remediated through periodic access reviews (access certification / attestation); IGA platforms automate review workflows and flag SoD (Segregation of Duties) violations",
      "Authenticator Assurance Levels (NIST SP 800-63B): AAL1 = some assurance that the claimant controls the authenticator; allows single-factor or multi-factor with less stringent requirements; AAL2 = high confidence; requires MFA, must be resistant to replay attacks; AAL3 = very high confidence; requires hardware-based MFA, mandates verifier impersonation resistance and phishing resistance; most enterprise environments target AAL2 minimum; government federal systems often mandate AAL3",
